{"title_page": "Geography of Ontario", "text_new": "{{Country geography <!-- Adapted for Province use -->\n|name            = Ontario\n|map             = Map_ont.jpg\n|continent       = [[North America]]\n|region          = [[North America]]<br/>[[Eastern Canada]]<br/>[[Central Canada]]\n|coordinates     = {{Coord|49|15|0|N|84|29|59|W}}\n|km area         = 917741\n|percent land    = 85.3\n|km coastline    = 3840\n|borders         = [[Land borders|Total land borders]]: U.S. states [[Michigan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Minnesota]]; Canadian provinces [[Manitoba]] and [[Quebec]]\n|highest point   = [[Ishpatina Ridge]]<br/>{{convert|693|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|lowest point    = [[Hudson Bay]]<br/>sea level\n|longest river   = [[Albany River]]<br/>{{convert|980|km|mi|abbr=on}}|largest lake    = [[Lake Superior]]<br/> 28,700&nbsp;km\u00b2 (11,080&nbsp;mi\u00b2)<br/>(Canadian portion only)\n}}\n\n'''[[Ontario]]''' is located in [[Eastern Canada|East]]/[[Central Canada|Central]] Canada. It is Canada's second largest province in total land area.  Its physical features vary greatly from the [[Mixedwood Plains Ecozone (Canada)|Mixedwood Plains]] in the southeast to the [[Taiga|boreal forests]] and [[tundra]] in the north.  Ontario borders Manitoba to the west,  [[Hudson Bay]] and [[James Bay]] to the north, [[Quebec]] to the east, and the [[Great Lakes]] and the [[United States]] to the south.   The province is named for Great [[Lake Ontario]], an adaptation of the [[Iroquois]] word ''Onitariio'', meaning \"beautiful lake\", or ''Kanadario'', variously translated as \"beautiful water\". There are approximately 250,000 lakes and over {{convert|100,000|km|mi}} of rivers in the province.\n\nAlmost 94% of the population is concentrated within [[Southern Ontario]], where the population was over 12,100,000 in the 2006 census. The [[Golden Horseshoe]] is the most populous part of Southern Ontario with a population of 8,102,163.<ref name=\"GHpopulation\">[http://geodepot.statcan.ca/Diss/Maps/ThematicMaps/horseshoe_e.cfm The population of communities in the Golden Horseshoe.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208012153/http://geodepot.statcan.ca/Diss/Maps/ThematicMaps/horseshoe_e.cfm |date=2006-12-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Population==\n[[Image:Cntower2.jpg|250px|right|thumb|The [[Toronto]] skyline seen from [[Toronto Harbour]]]]\nOntario is the most populous province in Canada. [[Southern Ontario]] is one of the densest regions in the country. [[Northern Ontario|The north]] is vast and sparse compared to the south. [[Ottawa]] (the nation's capital) is located in Ontario bordering Quebec. Located within the [[Golden Horseshoe]], [[Toronto]] is the capital of Ontario, the financial centre of Canada, and the country's most populous city.\n\nOntario is the second-most [[Urbanization|urbanized]] province after [[British Columbia]], with 85.9% of the population living in urban areas.<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/as-sa/98-310-x/98-310-x2011003_2-eng.cfm Canada's rural population since 1851]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Population by Statistical Area Classification<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table-Tableau.cfm?LANG=Eng&TABID=1&T=601&SR=1&RPP=25&S=0&O=D&CMA=0&PR=35#C2 Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories by the Statistical Area Classification, 2011 and 2006 censuses]</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan = \"2\" |Statistical Area Classification\n! colspan = \"2\" | 2011 Census\n! colspan = \"2\" | 2006 Census\n! rowspan = \"2\" | Change\n|-\n! Population\n! % of total\n! Population\n! % of total\n|-\n|Within CMAs  ||10,270,006 ||79.9% ||9,591,529 ||78.9% || {{profit}}7.1%\n|-\n|Within CAs  ||1,133,127 ||8.8% ||1,128,614 ||9.3% || {{profit}}0.4%\n|- style=\"background: lightblue\" \n| '''Total CMA/CA'''  ||11,403,133 ||88.7% ||10,720,143 ||88.2% || {{profit}}6.4%\n|-\n|Strongly influenced  ||644,299 ||5.0% ||631,410 ||5.2% || {{profit}}2.0%\n|-\n|Moderatel