.8 |4.4 |52.7\n|-12.5 |-5.6 |50.1\n|-24.9 |-15.7 |28.8\n|float  = left\n|clear  = none\n|source = <ref>[http://climate.weatheroffice.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_e.html?stnID=3914&lang=e&dCode=0&province=ONT&provBut=&month1=0&month2=12 Canadian Climate Normals 1971-2000 (Big Trout Lake)]</ref>\n}}\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Geography|Canada}}\n*[[Geology of Ontario]]\n*[[Geography of Canada]]\n*[[Demographics of Ontario]]\n*[[List of islands of Ontario]]\n*[[Southern Ontario]]\n*[[Ontario Peninsula]]\n*[[Northern Ontario]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.ontario.ca/en/about_ontario/EC001032.html?openNav=geography Geography of Ontario at www.ontario.ca]\n\n{{Ontario}}\n{{Subdivisions of Ontario}}\n{{Canada Geography}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Ontario| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Country geography <!-- Adapted for Province use -->\n|name            = Ontario\n|map             = Map_ont.jpg\n|continent       = [[North America]]\n|region          = [[North America]]<br/>[[Eastern Canada]]<br/>[[Central Canada]]\n|coordinates     = {{Coord|49|15|0|N|84|29|59|W}}\n|km area         = 917741\n|percent land    = 85.3\n|km coastline    = 3840\n|borders         = [[Land borders|Total land borders]]: U.S. states [[Michigan]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Minnesota]]; Canadian provinces [[Manitoba]] and [[Quebec]]\n|highest point   = [[Ishpatina Ridge]]<br/>{{convert|693|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n|lowest point    = [[Hudson Bay]]<br/>sea level\n|longest river   = [[Albany River]]<br/>{{convert|980|km|mi|abbr=on}}|largest lake    = [[Lake Superior]]<br/> 28,700&nbsp;km\u00b2 (11,080&nbsp;mi\u00b2)<br/>(Canadian portion only)\n}}\n\n'''[[Ontario]]''' is located in [[Eastern Canada|East]]/[[Central Canada|Central]] Canada. It is Canada's second largest province in total land area.  Its physical features vary greatly from the [[Mixedwood Plains Ecozone (Canada)|Mixedwood Plains]] in the southeast to the [[Taiga|boreal forests]] and [[tundra]] in the north.  Ontario borders Manitoba to the west,  [[Hudson Bay]] and [[James Bay]] to the north, [[Quebec]] to the east, and the [[Great Lakes]] and the [[United States]] to the south.   The province is named for Great [[Lake Ontario]], an adaptation of the [[Iroquois]] word ''Onitariio'', meaning \"beautiful lake\", or ''Kanadario'', variously translated as \"beautiful water\". There are approximately 250,000 lakes and over {{convert|100,000|km|mi}} of rivers in the province.\n\nAlmost 94% of the population is concentrated within [[Southern Ontario]], where the population was over 12,100,000 in the 2006 census. The [[Golden Horseshoe]] is the most populous part of Southern Ontario with a population of 8,102,163.<ref name=\"GHpopulation\">[http://geodepot.statcan.ca/Diss/Maps/ThematicMaps/horseshoe_e.cfm The population of communities in the Golden Horseshoe.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208012153/http://geodepot.statcan.ca/Diss/Maps/ThematicMaps/horseshoe_e.cfm |date=2006-12-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Population==\n[[Image:Cntower2.jpg|250px|right|thumb|The [[Toronto]] skyline seen from [[Toronto Harbour]]]]\nOntario is the most populous province in Canada. [[Southern Ontario]] is one of the densest regions in the country. [[Northern Ontario|The north]] is vast and sparse compared to the south. [[Ottawa]] (the nation's capital) is located in Ontario bordering Quebec. Located within the [[Golden Horseshoe]], [[Toronto]] is the capital of Ontario, the financial centre of Canada, and the country's most populous city.\n\nOntario is the second-most [[Urbanization|urbanized]] province after [[British Columbia]], with 85.9% of the population living in urban areas.<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/as-sa/98-310-x/98-310-x2011003_2-eng.cfm Canada's rural population since 1851]</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Population by Statistical Area Classification<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table-Tableau.cfm?LANG=Eng&TABID=1&T=601&SR=1&RPP=25&S=0&O=D&CMA=0&PR=35#C2 Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories by the Statistical Area Classification, 2011 and 2006 censuses]</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan = \"2\" |Statistical Area Classification\n! colspan = \"2\" | 2011 Census\n! colspan = \"2\" | 2006 Census\n! rowspan = \"2\" | Change\n|-\n! Population\n! % of total\n! Population\n! % of total\n|-\n|Within CMAs  ||10,270,006 ||79.9% ||9,591,529 ||78.9% || {{profit}}7.1%\n|-\n|Within CAs  ||1,133,127 ||8.8% ||1,128,614 ||9.3% || {{profit}}0.4%\n|- style=\"background: lightblue\" \n| '''Total CMA/CA'''  ||11,403,133 ||88.7% ||10,720,143 ||88.2% || {{profit}}6.4%\n|-\n|Strongly influenced  ||644,299 ||5.0% ||631,410 ||5.2% || {{profit}}2.0%\n|-\n|Moderately influenced  ||555,931 ||4.3% ||554,062 ||4.5% || {{profit}}0.3%\n|-\n|Weakly influenced  ||225,197 ||1.8% ||232,107 ||1.9% || {{loss}}3.0%\n|-\n|Not influenced  ||23,261 ||0.2% ||22,560 ||0.2% || {{profit}}3.1%\n|-  style=\"background: lightblue\" \n|'''Outside CMA/CA'''  ||1,448,688 ||11.3% ||1,440,139 ||11.8% || {{profit}}0.6%\n|-\n|'''Total'''  ||'''12,851,821''' ||'''100.0%''' ||'''12,160,282''' ||'''100.0%''' ||{{profit}}'''5.7%'''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Census Metropolitan Areas (CMAs) by population\n!City\n!2016 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table.cfm?Lang=Eng&T=201&S=3&O=D|title=Population and Dwelling Count Highlight Tables, 2016 Census|website=12.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n!2011 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/hlt-fst/pd-pl/Table-Tableau.cfm?LANG=Eng&T=202&PR=35&S=0&O=D&RPP=50|title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories, census metropolitan areas and census agglomerations, 2011 and 2006 censuses|website=12.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n!2006 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2006/dp-pd/hlt/97-550/Index.cfm?TPL=P1C&Page=RETR&LANG=Eng&T=202&SR=1&S=4&O=D&RPP=50&PR=35|title=Population and dwelling counts, for Canada, provinces and territories, census metropolitan areas and census agglomerations, 2006 and 2001 censuses - 100% data|website=12.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n!2001 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/english/census01/products/standard/popdwell/Table-CMA-P.cfm?T=1&PR=35&SR=1&S=1&O=A|title=Population and Dwelling Counts, for Canada, Provinces and Territories, Census Metropolitan Areas and Census Agglomerations, 2001 and 1996 Censuses - 100% Data|website=12.statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref> \n!1996 <ref name=\"statcan.gc.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/c1996-r1996/4129975-eng.htm|title=Population and Dwelling Counts, for Census Metropolitan : Areas in Decreasing Order of 1996 Population, 1991 and 1996 Censuses - 100% Data|website=Statcan.gc.ca|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n!1991 <ref name=\"statcan.gc.ca\"/>\n|-\n|[[Toronto]] ||5,928,040|| 5,583,064 ||5,113,149 ||4,682,897 || 4,263,757 || 3,898,933 \t\n|-\n|[[Ottawa]]-[[Gatineau]] ||1,323,783|| 1,236,324 || 1,130,761 ||1,063,664 || 1,010,498 || 941,814\n|-\n|[[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]] ||747,545|| 721,053 ||692,911 ||662,401 ||624,360 || 599,760\n|-\n|[[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Kitchener-Cambridge-Waterloo]] ||523,894|| 477,160 ||451,235 ||414,284||382,940 ||356,421\t\t\n|-\n|[[London, Ontario|London]] ||494,069|| 474,786 ||457,720 ||432,451 ||398,616 || 381,522\n|-\n|[[St. Catharines]]-[[Niagara Regional Municipality, Ontario|Niagara]] ||406,074|| 392,184 ||390,317 ||377,009 \t||372,406 || 364,552 \t\t\n|-\n|[[Oshawa]] ||379,848|| 356,177 ||330,594 ||296,298 ||268,773 || 240,104 \n|-\n|[[Windsor, Ontario|Windsor]] ||329,144|| 319,246 ||323,342 ||307,877 ||278,685 || 262,075\n|-\n|[[Barrie, Ontario|Barrie]] ||197,059|| 187,013 ||177,061 ||148,480 || 118,695 || 97,150\n|-\n|[[Greater Sudbury]] ||164,689|| 160,770 ||158